,Recommended,301320,31760213,Posted: 14 May,all,Syrsly,"Realistic roller coasters, perfect for the ultimate VR experience!I've been a VR player and Vive owner since October 2016, and NoLimits 2 is the only roller coaster game I keep coming back to for riding coasters.  It runs pretty well on less-than-optimal hardware (AMD Phenom II X4 955, no issues at all), and it even got a multi-core optimization update recently.  It's one of the few roller coaster simulators on Steam to take the realistic approach.The building tools are kind of dated and confusing.  I can't stress that enough.  It's not a good experience making coasters for this simulator.  It definitely takes tutorials and research to figure out how the park editor works.  There isn't a lot of documentation for this, either, that I could find.  Granted, I primarily got the app for riding coasters, not making them, so i gave up pretty quickly on building anything.  There is Workshop support, so you'll find a lot of coasters to ride.The VR controls are also non-existent.  You have to use the mouse and keyboard to navigate every bit of the game, from menu UIs to walking around parks.NoLimits 2 is worth the $40 if you have a Vive or Oculus or similar OSVR headset and want to experience realistic coaster rides.  I go into it every few weeks for 20-30 minutes at a time.  I also use it as a demo experience for my friends to try out roomscale VR."
